Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  string word; // input word
  int count = 0; // count variable

  cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
  cin >> word;

  ifstream file("filename.txt"); // replace "filename.txt" with your file name
  if (file.is_open()) {
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
      if (line.find(word) != string::npos) {
        count++;
      }
    }
    file.close();
  } else {
    cout << "Could not open file.";
    return 1;
  }

  cout << "The word \"" << word << "\" appears " << count << " times in the file." << endl;
  return 0;
}

In this program, we use the ifstream class to read the file line by line. We use the getline function to read each line into a string variable called "line". We then use the find function to search for the input word in each line. If the word is found, we increment the count variable. Finally, we print the total number of occurrences of the word to the console.

To use this program, replace "filename.txt" with the name of your text file and enter the word you want to search for at runtime. The program will then read the file and count the number of occurrences of that word.
